default&#xa0;
defaultIn the public debate about energy during recent years, there has been a lot of emphasis on electricity, but little about heat (or transport).  In overall terms, only about 35% of the primary energy consumed in the UK is used as electricity; the
default remaining 65% has two main forms of consumption, namely heat, where gas is the principal source, and transport, where oil is dominant.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhile industrial heat demand is reasonably constant, domestic demand is highly seasonal, being almost entirely temperat
defaulture dependent.  The 
defaultvariation
default between summer and winter demand is large and, because gas provides 80% of domestic properties (and a large proportion of smaller commercial premises) with heat, the demand for gas varies widely as the seasons change.  However
default, gas is well suited to this; it is much more flexible than electricity which has to be balanced instantaneously, whereas gas does not – it is normally balanced over a 24 hour period.
default              
defaultTerms of ReferencedefaultThere are others who are better placed than Oil &amp; 
defaultGas UK to answer the Committee’s 12 questions and so we are taking the opportunity to make some broader points relevant to this inquiry, but also answering the specific question about the relative merits of using gas in space heating.
